In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month. He acknowledges the impact of breast cancer on Americans and highlights the importance of prevention and early detection. The article emphasizes that older women and those with a personal or family history of breast cancer are at greater risk. President Obama encourages individuals to speak with their healthcare providers and visit www.Cancer.gov for more information on symptoms, diagnosis, and treatment. He also mentions that the Affordable Care Act ensures access to quality healthcare, including preventive services for women, such as mammograms. The President honors those who have been affected by breast cancer and recognizes the efforts of advocates, researchers, and healthcare providers in combating the disease. He urges citizens, government agencies, businesses, and nonprofit organizations to participate in activities that increase awareness and prevention of breast cancer.